# TypeScript

`strict` is assumed. Prefer parse-at-boundary over cast-through.

## Boundaries (where bugs enter)

External input (HTTP body/query, Server Actions, webhooks, env) → **Zod parse** → typed value. Shared schemas live in `@inabiya/validation` when FE and BE both need them (see checkout controllers).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — trust + cast
const total = (req.body as any).total as number;

// ✅ GOOD — pipe already used in Nest; same idea everywhere
@Body(new ZodValidationPipe(checkoutPlaceOrderBodySchema))
body: CheckoutPlaceOrderBody
```

## Do

- Discriminated unions / type guards instead of `as`
- `unknown` + Zod at JSON/webhook edges
- `satisfies` for config/payload shapes that must keep keys (`AccessPayload` pattern)
- Explicit return types on exported public APIs when inference hides intent
- Prisma enums / string unions + Zod — avoid numeric enums

## Don't

| Pattern | Why |
|---|---|
| `any` / `as unknown as T` | Hides invariants; needs a one-line justification if unavoidable |
| `foo!` non-null | Prefer early return / narrow |
| `@ts-ignore` | Use `@ts-expect-error` + reason, then fix |
| `number` for money | Use `*Paise: number` only as **integer paise**, never rupees float |

Money fields in this codebase are `subtotalPaise`, `totalPaise`, `amountPaise` (`Int` in Prisma). Keep that naming — don’t invent `price: number` rupees.
